<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="66" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="66">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="66">
This species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus deserticola" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="deserticola">Haplodrassus deserticola</taxonomicName>
from the Canary Islands (Figs 40-42, 50-51). 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus deserticola" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="deserticola">Haplodrassus deserticola</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus minor" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minor">Haplodrassus minor</taxonomicName>
by having a dorsal abdominal pattern (Fig. 66). 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus minor" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minor">Haplodrassus minor</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus deserticola" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="deserticola">Haplodrassus deserticola</taxonomicName>
also differ by the shape of the embolus (thick in 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus minor" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minor">Haplodrassus minor</taxonomicName>
, andthin in 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus deserticola" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="deserticola">Haplodrassus deserticola</taxonomicName>
), terminal apophysis (thick in 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus minor" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minor">Haplodrassus minor</taxonomicName>
, and thin in 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus deserticola" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="deserticola">Haplodrassus deserticola</taxonomicName>
), median apophysis (short in 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus minor" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minor">Haplodrassus minor</taxonomicName>
, and long in 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Gnaphosidae" genus="Haplodrassus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplodrassus deserticola" order="Araneae" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="deserticola">Haplodrassus deserticola</taxonomicName>
), epigyne and spermathecae.
</paragraph>
